# OSMEA Packages - Cursor Rules

## 📦 Overview
OSMEA Packages is a modular Flutter ecosystem designed to provide developers with a complete toolkit for building modern, scalable applications.

## 🎯 Development Guidelines

### 📁 Package Structure
```
packages/
├── components/          # UI Component Library
├── core/               # Foundation & Utilities
├── apis/               # Network Layer & API Integration
└── README.md           # Package Documentation
```

### 🏗️ Package Development Rules

#### 1. Package Naming
- **Package Name**: Use descriptive, lowercase names with underscores
- **Example**: `osmea_components`, `osmea_core`, `osmea_apis`
- **Version**: Follow semantic versioning (MAJOR.MINOR.PATCH)

#### 2. Dependencies Management
```yaml
# ✅ Good Example - pubspec.yaml
name: osmea_components
description: A comprehensive UI component library for Flutter applications
version: 0.1.0

environment:
  sdk: '>=3.0.0 <4.0.0'
  flutter: ">=3.19.0"

dependencies:
  flutter:
    sdk: flutter
  core:
    git:
      url: https://github.com/masterfabric-mobile/osmea.git
      path: packages/core

dev_dependencies:
  flutter_test:
    sdk: flutter
  flutter_lints: ^3.0.0
```

#### 3. Export Structure
```dart
// ✅ Good Example - Main library file
library osmea_components;

// Core exports
export 'src/components.dart';
export 'src/core/core.dart';
export 'src/enums/enums.dart';
export 'src/styles/styles.dart';
export 'src/theme/theme.dart';
export 'src/utils/utils.dart';

// Component-specific exports
export 'src/components/button/beautiful_button.dart';
export 'src/components/card/beautiful_card.dart';
// ... other component exports
```

### 🔄 Package Integration Rules

#### 1. Cross-Package Dependencies
- **Core Package**: Foundation for all other packages
- **Components Package**: Depends on Core
- **APIs Package**: Depends on Core
- **Applications**: Can depend on any combination of packages

#### 2. Dependency Injection
```dart
// ✅ Good Example - Package DI Setup
@module
abstract class ComponentsModule {
  @injectable
  ThemeService get themeService => ThemeService();
  
  @injectable
  ComponentRegistry get componentRegistry => ComponentRegistry();
}
```

#### 3. Configuration Sharing
```dart
// ✅ Good Example - Shared Configuration
class PackageConfig {
  static const String packageName = 'osmea_components';
  static const String version = '0.1.0';
  static const String description = 'UI Component Library';
  
  // Shared configuration across packages
  static const Map<String, dynamic> sharedConfig = {
    'theme': {
      'primaryColor': '#007AFF',
      'secondaryColor': '#5856D6',
    },
    'spacing': {
      'xs': 4.0,
      'sm': 8.0,
      'md': 16.0,
      'lg': 24.0,
      'xl': 32.0,
    },
  };
}
```

### 📚 Documentation Rules

#### 1. README Structure
```markdown
# Package Name

## Overview
Brief description of the package

## Features
- Key feature 1
- Key feature 2
- Key feature 3

## Installation
```yaml
dependencies:
  package_name:
    git:
      url: https://github.com/masterfabric-mobile/osmea.git
      path: packages/package_name
```

## Usage
Code examples and usage patterns

## API Reference
Detailed API documentation

## Examples
Links to example applications
```

#### 2. Code Documentation
```dart
/// A beautiful button component with multiple variants and sizes.
///
/// This component provides a consistent button interface across the application
/// with support for different styles, sizes, and states.
///
/// ## Example
/// ```dart
/// BeautifulButton(
///   text: 'Click me',
///   onPressed: () => print('Button pressed'),
///   variant: ButtonVariant.primary,
///   size: ButtonSize.medium,
/// )
/// ```
///
/// See also:
/// * [ButtonVariant] for available button styles
/// * [ButtonSize] for available button sizes
class BeautifulButton extends StatelessWidget {
  // Implementation
}
```

### 🧪 Testing Rules

#### 1. Test Structure
```
test/
├── unit/               # Unit tests
├── widget/             # Widget tests
├── integration/        # Integration tests
└── mocks/              # Mock objects
```

#### 2. Test Coverage
- **Unit Tests**: Test individual functions and classes
- **Widget Tests**: Test UI components
- **Integration Tests**: Test package interactions
- **Coverage Target**: Minimum 80% code coverage

#### 3. Test Examples
```dart
// ✅ Good Example - Widget Test
void main() {
  group('BeautifulButton', () {
    testWidgets('renders with correct text', (tester) async {
      await tester.pumpWidget(
        MaterialApp(
          home: Scaffold(
            body: BeautifulButton(
              text: 'Test Button',
              onPressed: () {},
            ),
          ),
        ),
      );

      expect(find.text('Test Button'), findsOneWidget);
    });

    testWidgets('calls onPressed when tapped', (tester) async {
      bool pressed = false;
      
      await tester.pumpWidget(
        MaterialApp(
          home: Scaffold(
            body: BeautifulButton(
              text: 'Test Button',
              onPressed: () => pressed = true,
            ),
          ),
        ),
      );

      await tester.tap(find.byType(BeautifulButton));
      expect(pressed, isTrue);
    });
  });
}
```

### 📦 Publishing Rules

#### 1. Version Management
- Use semantic versioning
- Update CHANGELOG.md for each release
- Tag releases in Git
- Document breaking changes

#### 2. Quality Assurance
- Run all tests before publishing
- Check code coverage
- Validate documentation
- Test in example applications

#### 3. Release Process
```bash
# 1. Update version in pubspec.yaml
# 2. Update CHANGELOG.md
# 3. Run tests
flutter test

# 4. Check code coverage
flutter test --coverage

# 5. Create Git tag
git tag v0.1.0

# 6. Push changes
git push origin main --tags
```

### 🔍 Code Quality Standards

#### 1. Linting
- Use `flutter_lints` package
- Configure custom lint rules
- Maintain consistent code style
- Fix all lint warnings

#### 2. Analysis
```yaml
# analysis_options.yaml
include: package:flutter_lints/flutter.yaml

linter:
  rules:
    - always_declare_return_types
    - avoid_print
    - prefer_const_constructors
    - prefer_final_fields
    - sort_child_properties_last

analyzer:
  exclude:
    - "**/*.g.dart"
    - "**/*.freezed.dart"
  errors:
    invalid_annotation_target: ignore
```

#### 3. Performance
- Optimize widget rebuilds
- Use const constructors
- Implement efficient algorithms
- Monitor memory usage

### 🚀 Best Practices

1. **Modularity**: Keep packages focused and single-purpose
2. **Reusability**: Design for reuse across different applications
3. **Performance**: Optimize for speed and efficiency
4. **Documentation**: Provide comprehensive documentation
5. **Testing**: Ensure high test coverage
6. **Maintainability**: Write clean, readable code

### 🔍 Code Review Checklist

- [ ] Package follows naming conventions
- [ ] Dependencies are properly managed
- [ ] Documentation is complete
- [ ] Tests are comprehensive
- [ ] Code quality standards are met
- [ ] Performance is optimized
- [ ] Security measures are in place
- [ ] Version is properly updated
- [ ] CHANGELOG is updated
- [ ] Example applications work correctly

